<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on SPI, Offer to Arnulfists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on SPI, Offer to Arnulfists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1505035294 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1505035294 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "RPC Television News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Dr. Ernesto Perez Balladares will retain the 
Institutional Protection Service [SPI] and will promote its 
professionalization. 
  As the president-elect sees it, it is important to insist on 
a coalition government. This is what he hinted when he learned 
of the Arnulfist's decision to reject two ministries he offered 
to them. 
  [Begin Perez Balladares recording] My offer was not an 
intention to create political slots, but an intention to create 
agreements, affinity, and to have the best men and women in the 
country for national projects. [end recording] 
  Perez Balladares said that the Legislative Assembly must 
approve the designation of the new comptroller general from a 
list of nominees he will submit when he takes over the 
government in September. 
  The president-elect was also asked about the future of the 
SPI. 
  [Begin Perez Balladares recording] I think that all 
presidential offices in all countries must have a protection 
service for people and institutions. I think this service must 
be professional, apolitical, and capable of fulfilling its 
functions. If I find these characteristics in the SPI, it will 
continue functioning exactly as it functions now. [end recording] 
  Perez Balladares said that he has a special office to answer 
the grievances of public employees who have been unjustly 
dismissed. He flatly rejected the possibility of an Arnulfist 
becoming president of the Legislative Assembly in September. 
  [Begin Perez Balladares recording] I believe that the 
legislative branch will have to make its own decisions, and I 
highly respect that. However, seeing how the Assembly is taking 
shape, I think that it will be presided over by the party that 
has obtained the most votes, and that is us. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

