<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Rejects Amnesty International Charge </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Rejects Amnesty International Charge </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1505175394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0130 GMT 15 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1505175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Diego Suarez from the "TV Today" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Colombian Government strongly protested today 
Amnesty International's charges of alleged human rights abuses 
by the Armed Forces and the police in Colombia. Amnesty 
International published full-page advertisements in two 
prominent London newspapers saying that the government allows 
the Colombian Army to murder with impunity. 
  The full-page ad by Amnesty International in London's THE 
INDEPENDENT and THE GUARDIAN newspapers, show a street youth 
sniffing glue. The caption explains that many of these children 
are killed by death squads paid by businessmen who want to clear 
the streets. 
  Amnesty International also states that the ad intends to 
irritate the Colombian Government, which is trying to convince 
the world that it is doing everything in its power to end the 
murders. Amnesty International also says that the Colombian 
Government wants to make believe that most murders are the work 
of drug traffickers, guerrillas, or a few wicked soldiers, but 
the truth is that most murders are committed by the Armed Forces 
or the police. The organization argues that the government does 
not want to face the Army and it says the Army is literally 
allowed to kill with impunity. 
  Finally, the ad expresses hope that the new president, who 
will be elected this month, will make human rights one of his 
top priorities. The ad was rejected by both spokesmen of the 
government and the military forces. The spokesmen described the 
ad as biased and as part of a guerrilla strategy to damage 
Colombia's image and the image of the Colombian Government 
abroad. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

