<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Caracas Mayor Says Transportation Strike Off </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Caracas Mayor Says Transportation Strike Off </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1705160894 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 
16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1705160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Maria Lilibeth Dacorte from the "Union Radio </F>
News" newscast] 
  [Text] According to Caracas Mayor Aristobulo Isturiz, the 
transportation strike set for Wednesday, 18 May, was called off 
because of meetings the Single Union of Independent Vehicles has 
held with the neighborhood committees to reach an agreement on 
an increase in the minimum fare. 
  [Begin Isturiz recording] Whenever fares are discussed, a 
strike is always announced as a pressure tactic. On Thursday, I 
met with this union, and I think the strike was suspended. The 
union accepted a timetable to hold bilateral discussions between 
the bus companies and the neighborhood associations and the 
community boards, but not between the bus companies and the 
neighborhood assemblies. [sentence as heard] An agreement has 
been reached with some bus companies, while the discussions 
continue with the others. [end recording] 
  Isturiz added that the increase in the minimal fare will be 
based on the service the bus line companies provide, the 
conditions of each bus, and the routes covered. For that reason, 
the minimual bus fare will range from 12 bolivares to 15 
bolivares. 

</TEXT>

