<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balaguer 'Declares Himself' Winner of Dominican Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balaguer 'Declares Himself' Winner of Dominican Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1805014294 Havana Cuba Vision Network in Spanish 0000 GMT 
18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1805014294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Cuba Vision Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dominican President Joaquin Balaguer has declared 
himself the winner of the presidential elections with a little 
over 43 percent of the votes counted, according to the ninth 
bulletin issued by the Central Electoral Commission of that 
country. The note states that more than 75 percent of the votes 
have already been counted. Balaguer leads his opponent Jose 
Francisco Pena Gomez by three points. 
  Reports indicate that the country remains quiet and that 
military patrols are more frequent in the face of electoral 
fraud claims, a claim also made in past elections. Pena Gomez, 
who is the candidate for the Dominican Revolutionary Party, the 
main opposition in the elections, stated that 200,000 of his 
followers were not allowed to vote. 
  [Begin recording] [Pena] I cannot say where this will end. 
We 
are talking about a fraud in the elections. The government and 
the Central Electoral Commission have an obligation to correct 
the situation. 
  [Balaguer] The elections have been fair. They claim that 
there has been so-called manipulation through the press, in 
complicity with foreign (?media). All these allegations must 
stand against the truth. The truth is stronger than anything. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

