<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Chief Says Executive Decisions on Military 'Correct' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Chief Says Executive Decisions on Military 'Correct' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1705044594 San Pedro Sula TIEMPO in Spanish 15 May 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> PA1705044594 </F>
<F P=104>  San Pedro Sula TIEMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tegucigalpa -- Armed Forces Chief General Luis 
Alonso Discua Elvir said Friday that the latest actions of 
President Carlos Roberto Reina regarding the Armed Forces are 
correct and, therefore, must not surprise anyone. 
  Gen. Discua attended the inauguration of the first 
industrial 
park of Comayagua. There, he was asked his opinion of the 
Executive Branch's decision to strip the Armed Forces of control 
over Hondutel [Honduran Telecommunications Enterprise] and other 
government institutions, as well as to establish voluntary 
military service. 
  The military chief affirmed that those decisions do not 
create differences between the Executive Branch and the Armed 
Forces. "I think that what is being done is correct," Gen. 
Discua explained. 
  Discua indicated that the agencies that were administered by 
the military had always belonged to the Executive, adding "this 
must not surprise anyone; these are just agencies that come 
under the Executive, and the managers must be appointed by the 
Executive." 
  In the meantime, Discua said he met with President Reina on 
Wednesday afternoon to analyze the problem of the increase of 
crime in the country. He concluded: "We have full support from 
the Executive to face the wave of criminality that has emerged." 

</TEXT>

