<F P=100> OUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Satellite Launch Discussed With Russians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Satellite Launch Discussed With Russians </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1705220394 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1223 GMT 17 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1705220394 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cordoba, 17 May (NA) -- Engineer Luis Murgio, one 
of the scientists from Cordoba Province who has developed a 
satellite that will be launched at the end of 1995, has 
travelled to Moscow to coordinate the launch with Russian 
authorities. 
  The first satellite from Cordoba was developed within the 
sphere of the province's Science and Technology Secretariat with 
the participation of a group of researchers that had worked on 
the now-deactivated Condor-II project. 
  The research activities were supported by the National 
Atomic 
Energy Commission in the province through the state enterprise 
CORATEC [expansion not given], which was created in 1992. 
  The project will have a final cost of some $1.2 billion, and 
it is thought that most of it has been built in Cordoba, 
although it does have some imported parts. 
  The satellite, which is the size of a shoe box, will be used 
for agricultural, geological, and environmental purposes. 

</TEXT>

