<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indians Threaten Government With Protests </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Indians Threaten Government With Protests </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1705130694 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 16 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1705130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the ""The Voz Andes Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Following an appeal by various Indian, trade union, 
and student groups to bring the country to a standstill, the 
government is expecting a restless week of protests by the 
people--probably with clashes between the demonstrators and the 
police. 
  Indian leaders warned Sixto Duran-Ballen that if Congress 
does not reject a draft agrarian law they consider harmful, they 
will close highways and isolate the capital. Luis Macas, 
president of the Confederation of Indian Nationalities of 
Ecuador, said that if this law is approved, Indians will fall 
back into the times of slavery. Our land would be taken away 
from us, and we would be unable to produce, he added. 
  Macas said that the law jeopardizes the Indians' ability to 
obtain food in the country, as it extends the landholders' 
controls over agricultural projects with the sole purpose of 
producing for export. Another Indian leader explained that the 
draft law seeks to eliminate the agrarian reform, which would 
deprive the Indian communities of their land. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

