Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   OAS Observers Report Election Irregularities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OAS Observers Report Election Irregularities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1905025394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0037 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1905025394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 18 May (EFE) -- The 27 OAS observers 
who witnessed the 16 May elections in the Dominican Republic 
said today that they detected irregularities and that many 
citizens were not able to vote. 
  The OAS report stated that "in several municipalities, 
citizens who had their identification cards could not vote due 
to irregularities in the official voters lists." In other 
words, the names of those citizens were not in the electoral 
register previously delivered to the political parties. The 
report added: "The OAS electoral mission, along with two other 
international delegations, immediately presented this serious 
concern to the Central Electoral Board (JCE) authorities. At 
the moment, we are not in a position to evaluate the magnitude 
or the implications of the irregularities in the electoral 
register." 
  The OAS observers hope the Dominican authorities will make 
an 
effort to determine "the identity of the persons responsible for 
the irregularities in the electoral registry." Finally, the OAS 
stressed "the preliminary status of the observations. Several 
members of the electoral mission will remain in the Dominican 
Republic to prepare a final report to be presented to the OAS 
Permanent Council as soon as possible." 
  Prior to the report's issuance, representatives from the 
U.S. National Democratic Institute for Foreign Affairs and 
members of Socialist International, SI, made similar 
observations, expressed in even stronger terms. A spokesman for 
President Ballaguer's Social Christian Reformist Party today 
described the SI observers as "insolent," adding that "none of 
them have any right to meddle in our national politics." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

