Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coffee Growers Satisfied With Prices </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coffee Growers Satisfied With Prices </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1705212794 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 17 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1705212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Manizales -- The National Coffee Growers Association 
received with satisfaction and moderate optimism the report that 
coffee prices had closed at $1.45 a pound on international 
coffee markets. 
  The Association believes the government should take 
advantage 
of those circumstance to adjust coffee prices to a point more 
equitable than that existing when the world quota agreement was 
interrupted. 
  Association sources reported Finance Minister Rudolf Hommes 
as saying that if this price holds for at least 30 days, the 
government would consider a new adjustment. 
  In addition, the Cooperative of Caldas Coffee Growers has 
reported a drop in local reserves and that the marketing of the 
mid-season crop has been reduced by 500,000 arrobas compared to 
the same period last year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

