<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1705230394 </F>
<F P=103> PA1705230394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments monitored through 17 May. 
  Colombian sugar exports increased 27.7 percent in 1993 while 
sugar production fell 0.33 percent. This drop meant that 1.833 
million tons of sugar were produced in 1993 compared to 1.839 
tons in 1992. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 7 May 94 
p 3B) 
  As of 12 May, 125 kg of coffee will be sold at a price of 
132,000 pesos, which constitutes a 10-percent increase over the 
former price. The National Committee of Coffee-Growers agreed 
on this price readjustment on 11 May. The increase obtained 
will give the National Coffee Fund additional revenues of 70 
billion pesos. (Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 12 May 94) 
  The financial system continues to have liquidity problems. 
The interbanking rate dropped to 35-percent annually. Savings 
accounts are growing at an average rate of 44-percent. An 
increase in imports has helped increase the current dollar 
exchange price to 841 pesos. Interest rates are stable. The 
inflation rate for the first trimester of 1994 has been around 
12 percent. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 15 May 94 p 
2B) 

</TEXT>

