<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Pays $25 Million in Overdue Interest </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Pays $25 Million in Overdue Interest </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1905011694 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 17 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1905011694 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Today, Ecuador paid international banks the first 
$25 million of overdue interest, thus beginning to comply with 
an agreement whereby this amount must be paid two weeks after 
the refinancing announcement was made on 3 May. Government 
sources said that another $25 million, equivalent to $5 million 
monthly for overdue interest from January to May, will be 
disbursed in three days. The amount is due before Friday. 
  Two weeks ago, the Ecuadoran Government agreed to refinance 
the country's commercial debt of $7.5 billion over a 30-year 
period with a 15-percent write off with banks. This operation 
will make it possible for the country to refinance its debt with 
the Paris Club and other lending organizations. 
  Ecuador's total debt borders on $13 billion, Latin America's 
largest per capita. The $13-billion debt is equivalent to $1,000 
for each of the country's 13 million inhabitants. Shortly before 
reaching this agreement with the creditor banks, President Sixto 
Duran-Ballen paid $5 million in April as a gesture of good faith 
and seriousness, Finance Minister Cesar Robalino reported at the 
time. With this payment, Ecuador ended a 20-month delay in the 
payment of overdue interest, which had accumulated up to a total 
of $2.5 billion since 1987. As for the remaining principal, 
approximately $5 billion, the country will choose among several 
alternatives proposed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

