<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1705224394 </F>
<F P=103> PA1705224394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments monitored through 17 May. 
  Finance Minister Julio Sosa Rodriguez has announced that 
Venezuela became a member of the Multilateral Investment 
Guarantees Agency (MIGA) on 6 May by paying the $3,088,038 that 
corresponds to the 20-percent subscription fee. By joining MIGA, 
Venezuela acquires more guarantees in the flow of foreign 
investment. (Caracas EL GLOBO in Spanish 10 May 94 p 12) 
  The Venezuelan Central Bank (BCV) reported on 10 May that 
the 
people have no need to fear an unstable bolivar, because the 
drop in international reserves has been curbed. BCV President 
Antonio Casas said, "There is no reason not to have faith in the 
bolivar and in the country's economic future." The dollar 
experienced a setback on 29 April when the bolivar rose from 
118.30 per dollar to 123.50. On 10 May, the bolivar closed at 
131.50. (Madrid EFE in Spanish 0112 GMT 11 May 94) 
  Foreign Trade Institute President Alberto Poletto has 
announced that the abrupt break in trade talks between Colombia, 
Mexico, and Venezuela to form a trade zone under the Group of 
Three "does not mean the end or failure of the negotiations." 
The foreign trade ministers of Mexico, Colombia, and Venezuela 
will strive in the coming days to overcome the impasse created 
in Bogota when Mexico tried to impose conditions the other two 
countries did not accept. (Caracas REPORTE DE LA ECONOMIA in 
Spanish 11 May 94 p 20) 
  Finance Ministry sources have reported that imports have 
experienced a 40-percent decline. It is estimated that in 1994 
exports will reach 10.2-10.5 billion dollars, compared to 1993's 
10.9 billion dollar figure. According to the same sources, in 
1993 the country sustained an economic reduction of 1 percent, 
which is expected to reach 1.5 percent in 1994. (Caracas EL 
NACIONAL in Spanish 11 May 94 p E-2) 
  During the first three months of 1994, Venezuela experienced 
a slowdown characterized by spiraling inflation and declines in 
the basic economic indicators. This is reflected in an economic 
report prepared by the Presidency's Office of Coordination and 
Planning. The price of oil, which is a touchstone used to assess 
the country's revenues, was $12.33 per barrel, showing a 
4.8-percent decline when compared to prices recorded in the last 
three months of 1993. (Caracas Union Radion Network in Spanish 
1100 GMT 17 May 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-57465 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat097_a_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-097 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civilian Army Said Ready To Prevent `Farce' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Civilian Army Said Ready To Prevent `Farce' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1805213794 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 1930 GMT 
18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1805213794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jose Francisco Pena Gomez, leader of the opposition 
Dominican Revolutionary Party [PRD], who had reported fraud in 
the 16 May elections held in the Dominican Republic, said today 
that he has a civilian army ready to prevent an election farce. 
  We do not accept the results provided by the Central 
Electoral Board, which gives a slight advantage to President 
Joaquin Balaguer, Pena Gomez said in a television program. He 
also demanded a review of all vote tally sheets. 
  Pena Gomez also referred to his remarks during the 1994 
elections, when he said that fraud must be proven before a call 
for violence could be made. 
  In a letter addressed to the Central Electoral Board, Jose 
Francisco Pena Gomez demands the suspension of the vote count 
due to the despicable, serious irregularities detected during 
the process. If the vote count continues, Balaguer would be 
proclaimed president, he said. 
  Moreover, Chilean Luis Ayala, chairman of Socialist 
International for Latin America, has denounced serious 
irregularities in the general elections held on Monday [16 May] 
in the Dominican Republic. 
  In a news conference, Ayala supported the denunciations made 
by the PRD presidential candidate who said he would be present 
today at the Central Electoral Board to refute the process and 
demand new elections in those districts where thousands of 
citizens were unable to vote. 
  Luis Ayala added that Socialist International delegates, in 
the Dominican Republic to observe the elections at the 
invitation of Pena Gomez, have detected serious and grave 
irregularities. Ayala added that citizens linked to Balaguer's 
government had two identification cards. 
  Balaguer was leading when the latest vote count results were 
announced. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

