<F P=100> Inter-Caribbean Affairs </F>
<F P=101> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Cites Observer `Interference' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Cites Observer `Interference' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2005034294 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0224 GMT 20 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2005034294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 19 May (NOTIMEX) -- Today, official 
sources reported the Government of the Dominican Republic has 
denounced the alleged interference of journalists and 
international observers in Monday's electoral process. 
  The Foreign Ministry warned that if state security is 
violated, the authorities will try to stop these actions, which 
are considered "antidemocratic" and which have sometimes been 
carried out in a "veiled" manner and "brazenly blatant" in 
others. 
  In a communique issued this evening, the Foreign Ministry 
stated that the alleged interference of the media and 
international envoys is part of an "international conspiracy to 
unite Haiti and Santo Domingo." The document, signed by Foreign 
Minister Juan Aristides Taveras, added that the actions carried 
out during and after the electoral process by the media and 
international observers "is definitely unacceptable." 
  In an interview with the U.S. network Telemundo, Dominican 
President Joaquin Balaguer said the reports of fraud issued by 
the opposition do not alter the social peace that prevails in 
Santo Domingo after the general elections. "I believe this is 
an international plot rather than a result of Pena Gomez' 
claims; this has something to do with the Haitian problem, and 
it is the old idea of integrating the two countries," the 
87-year-old Balaguer said. 
  On Thursday [19 May], the Dominican Revolutionary Party 
(PRD) 
began to gather the necessary evidence to prove the alleged 
fraud perpetrated in Monday's general elections. Social 
Democrat Francisco Pena Gomez ordered his lawyers to prepare the 
corresponding writs and lists, with names and voters numbers, of 
party members who were not able to vote in different provinces. 
  Pena Gomez said the complete set of documents will be 
delivered to the Central Electoral Board (JCE) and "to the world 
as proof of the colossal fraud perpetrated against us." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

