<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Fidel Castro Stops Over in Brazil </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Fidel Castro Stops Over in Brazil </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1505145194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0332 GMT 12 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1505145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Salvador, Brazil, 11 May (PL) -- Cuban President 
Fidel Castro arrived today in this northeastern Brazilian city 
during a service stopover on his return flight from South Africa 
to Cuba. 
  The Cuban president visited Pretoria, the South African 
capital, where he participated in the inauguration of President 
Nelson Mandela. 
  The Cubana de Aviacion flight landed at the Dos de Julio Air 
Base in the capital of Bahia state, where Fidel Castro and his 
entourage were greeted by current Governor Antonio Imbassahy, 
former governor Carlos Magalhaes, Ramon Sanchez Parodi, the 
Cuban ambassador to Brazil, and other local personalities. 
  This is the second time the Cuban president has visited 
Salvador and the fourth time he has visited Brazil. 
  Fidel visited Brasilia in early 1990 for the presidential 
inauguration that year. In June 1992 he attended the world 
summit on the environment in Rio de Janeiro, and in July 1993 he 
visited Salvador Bahia to participate in the third 
Ibero-American conference. 
  According to official sources cited by the local press, the 
Cuban president will remain approximately 12 hours in Brazilian 
territory, although no official agenda was announced for his 
visit. 
  Organizations of friendship and solidarity with Cuba as well 
as other associations in Bahia said they wanted to give Fidel 
Castro a great reception. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

