<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreement on Passenger, Cargo Flights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agreement on Passenger, Cargo Flights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1905143394 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2338 GMT 18 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1905143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Javier Rodriguez] </F>
  [Text] Havana, 18 May (PL) -- Today in this capital, Cuba 
and Colombia signed an agreement of understanding that will lead 
to the establishment of regular flights of the two countries' 
airlines. 
  The document was signed by Fernando Zarama, Colombian 
director of national civil aviation, and Argimiro Ojeda Vives, 
vice president of the Cuban Civil Aeronautics Institute (IACC). 
  The agreement specifies that airlines from the two Latin 
American nations may offer passenger, cargo, and mail services 
regularly and independently from the current weekly charter 
flights. 
  The agreement was the result of negotiations between 
delegations from the two countries with the participation of 
representatives of Cubana de Aviacion and the Colombian 
airlines, namely, SAM, Avianca, Intercontinental, Islena, and 
Transportes Aereos Mercantiles Panamericanos (Tampa). 
  Also present at the talks were Manuel Leal, representing the 
Association of Colombian Air Transporters, as well as other IACC 
and Cubana de Aviacion officials. 
  During the signing ceremony, Zarama described as important 
the agreement that established bilateral aeronautics relations, 
which reflect the friendship and solidarity that exist between 
the two nations. 
  Meanwhile, Colombian Ambassador to Cuba Ricardo Santamaria 
underscored the coincidence between the conclusion of the 
negotiations, a visit to Cuba by the Colombian Navy's school 
ship "Arc Gloria," and the conclusion of a visit to Havana of a 
delegation of businessmen interested in investing in the island. 
  Santamaria said the happy conclusion to the negotiations was 
the product of the Cubans' constructive attitude. He said that 
Cuba can count on Colombia as a loyal and friendly partner. 
  Ojeda underscored Cuba's satisfaction with the agreements 
and 
the need for unity and cooperation between the region's airlines 
from underdeveloped countries in order to survive and offer the 
services that their peoples require. 
  He said the ceremony took place on the 65th anniversary of 
Cubana de Aviacion and pointed out that it contributes to the 
development of relations between Colombia and Cuba. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
